column1: Between 4 February 2022 and 4 August 2022, will anti-government protests in Russia result in ten or more fatalities?
column6: ['Society', 'Security and Conflict', 'Non-US Politics']
Not their modus operandi.
For passage of time
There are no signs of dissent that would lead to this type event

I suspect this body count threshold has likely already been surpassed, but evidence of what has happens deep within the Russian security apparatus is an information black hole. Sadly, we may never know ground truth, but it is nevertheless highly unlikely such reporting will emerge in the short time left for this market question.
Here is an excerpt from a recent article in Foreign Policy (https://www.foreignaffairs.com/russian-federation/putins-new-police-state , July 27):
There already could have been fatalities. But Russia will do everything to cover it up.
There will be deaths. There probably already have been. But Russia will do everything it can to cover them up.
Sanktion are not bothering the public enough yet.
Clear evidence about fatalities due to the Russian crackdown remain very difficul.
Most analysts are looking to later this year, possibly after September, for the sanctions regimes to take hold in Russia.

Russia is not the USA. Protestors will be arrested but killing them is very unlikely either by the authorities or right-wing movements.

it seems the Russian population has accepted the War, and major protests are unlikely.
It's probably easier to flee and leave the country than to look for trouble with the soviets.
Not sure whether the question requires all 10 to occur as the result of the same protest or whether it's cumulative. I will interpret as the former.
I'm keeping this at 1 rather than 0 just because of reports claiming arson attacks on recruitment centers. Doubt they are that widespread or likely to be fatal, but it's not nothing
The popularity of the existing Russian regime, even in the face of the existing slate of sanctions and death toll in the Ukraine war, suggests a lower probability.
The scenario is well plausible but only if the credible sources can confirm timely….
At this point I think there are three things at work:
While dissatisfaction with the war is growing, the likelihood of significant protests in the next three month is lower because the economy is holding up.

Passage of time. Ukraine war will clearly not directly trigger deadly protests. Other triggers (e.g., food shortages or other collapses in basic services) may become credible eventually, but are exceedingly unlikely to unfold within our timeframe. All in.
updating lower
No indications for something like that yet, already 3 months into the question (and 3 more before question ends).
From the outside it does not look like the protests are getting momentum.

To me, it look like the opposition in Russia is to dismanteled to stage the large scale demonstrations that would warrant large scale policy/military violent action. I must stay I am a little surprised, but it seems that there is a reason why Russia has a history of autocratic ruling - Russians seem to like a «strong» leader.
With arrests in the thousands, the economy tanking and protests showing no end in sight, people will become more desperate.

NATO and NATO members will not openly enter the conflict and they will progressively take a distance from the Ukranian government as the true emerges over Kiev's a very dubious conduct of the war, not able to control ultra-nationalists militias and their crimes. UN will take over in conducting peace talks, in a multilateral climate of collaboration with China. Russians will realize Putin was not so wrong about the need of "denazify" Ukraine after all

There have been no signs that mass protests are likely to happen in Russia even less that they could turn violent to the rate which could result in fatality. Russian society has learned that resistance is futile.
Although the Russian government may not admit it.

The state propaganda machine has kicked into full gear regarding how the "special operation" in Ukraine is going. The actions taken to block and shut down almost all independent media outlets and new laws on military censorship has had an impact on the success/failure of street protests. That said, it is hard to ignore the reports of Russian military deaths and injuries that are coming out of the region. Coupled with the uptick of reporting on atrocities in places like Bucha, that could place more strain on the security apparatus to contain.

Super high approval for Putin/regime plus Russia has avoided default and stabilized the ruble. My original forecast I calculated 5% base rate and bumped it to 10% due to the sharpness of the economic fallout. With passage of time base rate is now 4% and I'm adjusting down from that since regime approval is high and the regime seems stable internally so far.
Who decides if a death was attributed to protest is still unclear-
the longer it gets dragged out, the more likely this becomes.

I was already below the crowd but I'm going back down further. At this point, there haven't been any protests big enough such that there would be a risk of fatal violence by law enforcement (which has a very low base rate per previous forecasts https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1409514), and the question resolves in the middle of summer, which is unlikely to be when things get much worse for the Russian people.

Rethinking my earlier stance here, The highest probability for protests to occur was right after the war was announced, and the intensity of protests have waned since then. The only probability of this increasing is incase the economic consequences of the sanctions become so severe that people feel they have nothing to lose, that looks unlikely, for now atleast. https://news.sky.com/story/moscow-looks-the-same-but-is-utterly-transformed-12567609 https://unherd.com/thepost/post-sanctions-life-in-moscow-is-not-all-that-different/
Great probability that there would be though being closed as they are might not know about it till after
Perhaps there will be deaths, but reliable (aka truthful) reporting is limited in Russia. Putin has been downplaying the protests, so even if there are deaths, we might not hear about it.

There's a chance of larger protests if the dissent on what was and was not covered from the Feb-March conflict grows and when the troops return home, but there are measures in place already to prevent protests, and likely will be in the future.

Putin’s recent comments on “spitting out flies” indicate a purge of political/intelligence/military within RU and is suggestive of the fact that he is concerned about his own position. Perceives existential risks to autocrats would often suggest greater use of violence to maintain power. However, RU police are pretty adept at dishing out enough violence to deter people but not enough to create martyrs. The 15% chance is of demonstrations reaching boiling point and a general sense of imminent collapse from the regime resulting in a sudden change of policing/suppression policy a la Tiananmen Sq. Given that tens of thousands of Russians are fleeing the country as they see no future in it, it seems that some of those most motivated to fight the regime are choosing to leave rather than resist. It seems then less likely that critical pressure will build, esp. since RU seem keen to negotiate due to military failure of operation and weight of sanctions. All in all, the combination of mass exodus, willingness to negotiate and adept use of violence by RU police suggest this will not happen.
At this point, all it takes is one coordinated effort by vocal dissenters for Russia to crack down and deliver a counter message.

At first, I was fairly certain this would happen, as Russia was tightening all laws against expressing any views that differ from official propaganda. But police seem to be going out of their way not to inflict life-threatening injuries. I just saw one video that showed multiple officers physically picking up a protester and carrying the person off. That's very different from beating a protester into submission, let alone shooting. Police must be under orders to use restraint. The question is, how long will this restraint continue? Will it continue for almost 5 months? Between now and then likely lies enormous problems in Ukraine, mounting military deaths, and massive economic problems.
I have two thoughts on this, both are reflected in my answer:
This is possible, but the efficiency of Russian security forces in arresting protesters does reduce the chances of enough of them gathering in a single place to create damage.

Surprising that with over 13K arrested so far that there has not been deaths reported, or at least as far we we know. https://www.dw.com/en/russian-activists-defy-putin-to-protest-war-in-ukraine/a-61073902. The main concern is that as long as this drags on the likelihood of a death, either someone in active protest or someone already in custody, increases dramatically as the sanctions begin to take their toll on the population.

My current reassessment of this scenario is that the likelihood of repression is lower than I had hoped because of so much preemptive repression. Autocrats do not gamble with wars so readily without having measures in place to deal with domestic repercussions.
Hedging to the crowd, because I'm not sure which way this will go.
Protests will increase as the body count increases

The Russian authorities probably aren't going to gun down protestors. They are more likely to continue their traditional ceremony of arresting them and then murdering them while they're in custody, without necessarily mentioning this to anybody. These will not be fatalities "due to an injury incurred during a protest," although without the protest they wouldn't have happened. The fatalities, if anyone hears about them at all, will be reported as down to heart attacks or suicides after the protests.

I believe the crowd here is wildly underestimating the probability of deadly clashes. The reference class isn't recent Russian protests, but "anti-government protests against unpopular and failing authoritarian regimes"

There have been reports of many detainments following anti-government protests Thus far no fatalities from injuries acquired during the actual protest. With the number of people involved in protests and their atmosphere, possible that at least an accidental death may occur from the protest 10 or more fatalities
Losing the total control of media
As the economy collapses, there will be more protests, more about high prices and shortages than politics, which will be brutally quashed.
THe brutality of the Russsian police and the Putin regime together with the mass protest may cause death during the next half year with a high probability
base rates: 3% of protests lead to deaths 3.5% of the population needed to bring about a serious change (russia's population is 144 million)

Dialing down my probability slightly based on this assessment. Sanctions will have consequences on the general populace and that might evoke stronger protests from people in the near future - a possibility that needs to be monitored. For now it does not seem as if the protests are widespread or gaining traction. https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2022/mar/10/vladimir-putin-regime-anti-war-protests-russia-russian
In this sense, we have seen what has happened so far. Actually, I don't see any basis that this scenario, which is very likely, will result in a different way.

Estimates assess the number of protesters killed in Kazakstan in January at over 200, but these were not Russian citizens in Russia. While reliable reports of any deaths or disappearances of protesters in Russia have yet to surface, there is a better than even chance that at least few of those thus far identified as organizers will experience "heath problems" in prison. Others may simply disappear. Would this judgment be confirmed by the deaths of soldiers who are killed for defection or dereliction off duty? What is the universe of actions constituting anti-government protests? Confirming such outcomes shielded in the Russian info sphere will make assessing the accuracy of this judgment very difficult. Regardless, we do know that the speed of Russian escalation in Ukraine has been fast and discernible so one could expect similar escalation against any signs of protest in Mother Russia. By, Summer, the repercussions of this military overreach will have hit civilians hard. This scenario will drive more people to a Bobby MaGee mentality; "freedom is just another word for nothing left to loose." Whether confirmable or not, more Russians will engage in acts perceived as anti-government over the next several months and dozens will die or "disappear."
But, we won’t know it from official announcements.
So far protests have not met with all that much violence, but a change is far from impossible. An educated guess.
Anti-Putin sentiment is increasing
The question is completely meaningless, because it will never be possible to verify whether they were victims or not.

The Russian people have until now been too afraid to protest en masse. But thousands have been arrested, and many beaten. If Putin closes the borders the young people will see no future, either inside or outside of Russia. It only takes one major event over the next 5 months, so I'll overweight "YES," with 71%.
Probably has already occurred. With Western media pretty much barred or restricted from reporting in Russia, we can't trust anything coming out of the country.

I think there would have to be a significant increase in unrest for this to occur. But with the major banks and rating agencies predicting a debt default by Russia in mid April this will make financing extremely difficult. They are trying to increase payments to lower income people to make up for the heavy inflation they are going to suffer. They can't achieve this if they can't finance effectively finance themselves (3 year bond @ 20%). They may try and print there way out of this but it will only exacerbate the issue. It will have a massive negative impact on Russians

What would have to happen for this to occur: - protests would have to become far larger / more common and to change their nature; - anti-protest measures would need to feel obliged to resort to use of force beyond just demonstrative muscle - this would require either real ill will or a perception of significant threat; - any deaths occurring would need to actually be reported, which might not be a given in current times. That all seems pretty unlikely.
Ten? .... TEN?
Probably there are already but we will not know about them.
there is a continued uptick in protesting/demonstrations - unrest continues to grow, i think its only a matter of time

Rumours of serious negotiations between Putin and Zelensky means that Putin may be able to salvage something he can pass off as a win in the near future https://www.jpost.com/international/article-700677 .

Economic sanctions against Russia will probably lead to higher inflation and unemployment. If the war in Ukraine drags on for weeks or even months, the chance of protests becoming riots is increasing, and so the chance of state violence against those rioters. On the other hand, Russia's security forces are quite capable in dispersing protesters without killing them (see for example 2011 protests).

Increasing my probability with the increasing severity of retaliation against protestors. With independent media reporting abilities curtailed, data on sporadic fatalities might be hard to come by unless the scale of protests increase massively

Protests in Russia have already reached a scale where escalation between protesters and government forces is likely. Economic pressure is starting to build on ordinary Russians could result in greater Russians becoming more violent against government forces. Unlikely to get any reliable source to confirm fatalities though.
Even if it actually happened, it would be denied.

Protests of the Russian invasion of Crimea in 2014, proceeded under heavy police supervision [per Washington Post article at the time]. There were minor scuffles between pro-Russian supporters, but no serious violence or arrests. Russian intelligentsia may protest on ethical principle, but are more likely to pursue a path of persuasion over violence. Assembling large numbers of people willing to perpetrate or endure violence requires something less lofty than principles and those conditions might be achieved if the Russian economy implodes. The West has the means, though perhaps not the collective will - because it too will feel the pain - to collapse the Russian economy and trigger a leadership challenge and concomitantly violent protests.

Autocratic regimes certainly have a proclivity towards killing their own during protests: those unlucky enough to be caught in the crosshairs of a rooftop sniper or caught underfoot of a fast-moving policy truck certainly - in the eyes of security forces - will deter the rest from coming out.
We already have several and people are fleeing from Russia toward Finland and Poland.
Protests seem to be growing, and arrests with them. But Russian laws are becoming more restrictive. I think the Russian government will continue to become more repressive.
Summer is the risk for civil unrest in any society. That said it feels like the Russian regime is locking down society and moving towards a more totalitarian stance.

Russian population in major cities has been participating in growing protests in major cities (St. Petersburg, Moscow, Novosibirsk) since the beginning of the conflict. The government is getting increasingly militant in managing these protests which makes it more likely to have a confrontation with deadly force.

My estimate assumes a high likelihood of death assuming the protests continue, which in turn is a function of the likelihood that the Ukraine war continues. The proliferation of the protests across Russia (assuming the western media is correct) is significant in the recent past, and while the Russian media is focused on clamping down free press, it seems that social media makes this near impossible. The compound probability is something like p(deaths) = p(deaths | protests) * p(protests), and P(protests) = p(protests | war) * p(war). In my thinking, p(death) = (0.66) * (0.95) * (0.4) = ~ 25%

Starting with a low estimate of likelihood. Will have to wait and monitor how the economy holds up to sanctions with the cost of invading Ukraine. If the economy continues to disintegrate in Russia this will lead to more demonstrations and protest.
They have, and will, but the media won't be covering it.
Unlikely due to the possible international outcry
The Committee of Moms in Moscow has begun to stage marches which are being suppressed in a riotous display of state authority.
It will be difficult to validate evidence of fatalities even if it did happen.

This question comes up every time there are large demonstrations in Russia. You are much more likely to die in a protest action in the USA than in Russia. The police seem to be more disciplined in Russia and the far-right not evangelical Christian in ideology.
Very likely to happen if it hasn't already. The real uncertainty. one suspects, is whether it will be disclosed or discovered before this question times out.

I'd say there is a fair chance that it has already occurred. Additionally, the public doesn't know about what goes on behind closed doors, which means that how the arrested protesters is being treated is even more hidden from the already very controlled media. On the otherhand, the protests don't seem to be escalating to the point of large scale violent police action.

I agree with @mattlerner and @MrLittleTexas. I did not find data showing any protester deaths in Russia in the last 20 years, and that would definitely be a major problem for the Kremlin. Our latest precedent, the 2021 protests that erupted due to Navalny's murder attempt, show zero fatalities too.

I feel like the answer will be yes as it is cumulative over a time period where the people who protest will be those who feel strongest and with a government who doesn’t seem too concerned with the reasons restraint was implemented in the past. Russians already fear martial law, and so any protesting in that climate risks escalation. And if there are large mobilisations, which won’t come for a couple of months (planning and build up needed) the response is likely to be harsher. Indiscriminate arrests including children, and older people protesting and getting arrested are also more likely to increase accidents if only because others might be more likely to intervene in stopping the arrest!

This is just the initial forecast. There have been some really well thought out comments on base rates with past protests. The only new factor (relative to the past protests, which were all political protests), will be the repercussions the sanctions will have on the Russian economy and hence the population. Even if Putin does achieve what he wants, the outcome could be worse for the general population if the sanctions worsen (The EU and US haven't yet sanctioned Russian Oil and Gas supplies which account for roughly 36% of federal revenues). Will revise my forecast as the war progresses.
Turns out that even the 1991 Soviet Coup attempt didn't result in >10 fatalities. This is definitely not common.

Governments worldwide, even authoritarian ones, are very averse to openly killing protesters, because it's terrible for propaganda purposes and can galvanize much more intense protests. So events have to get quite bad for this to happen.

Russia is tilting far further into authoritarianism, and the government will be increasingly likely to employ repressive and violent measures to achieve its goals. However, people know this and will therefore be less likely to go to protests in the near term. But at some point, when unemployment and hunger are much more widespread, I think they will likely protest anyway, until they are deterred with more violence. I think the Russian economy is going to collapse, and then either Putin will be ousted in a palace coup, as he loses the support of even the elites, or the palace will rally around him. I could picture anti-government protests that turn violent in the lead-up and aftermath of both scenarios.

I'm not sure that the current approach of massive immediate crack down and arrest of single potential protestor is sustainable. Some more organised protests will probably be tried and the response will be brutal.
I'm using Black Lives Matter protest data as a ballpark proxy and doubling to account for "uniqueness" of situation. I join @mattlerner and @alh in their reasoning.

The war and the sanctions are in their early phases... protests and their suppression/prevention/diversion are likely to rise in the coming months... Putin's control may weaken, increasing the likelihood of fatalities.

As the Ukraine invasion continues and associated sanctions against Russia hurt its economy, more and more Russians will presumably take to the streets to express their displeasure with Putin’s despotic government, and some may well go farther to agitate for a new leader. Far from clear that fatalities will occur as the number of protest actions continues to increase, but there seems to be a very credible chance of this. I’ll also point out that fatalities can be accidental—stampedes or exposure to winter elements could cause fatalities even without any direct aggression by Russian goons/police, especially if very large numbers of people get involved and protest over extended time periods. As this question is worded, such fatalities could presumably count too, assuming that reporters manage to somehow be able to report these.
Okay, we want to know P(10 fatalities, protest)

While I think its highly likely that Russian protests will be ongoing and have potential for violence two things impact the lower than 50/50. Crowd control measures in Russia will probably be strictly enforced. As much as I want to compare this scenario to the Hunger Games, I don't think mass troop firing into protests will be authorised. The other reason is if fatalities do happen, will they be reported?
As conditions for everyday folks get worse, the possibility of larger, more violent protests rises.

It is almost certain a handful of people will die. Whether this number will exceed 10 is another question. The second problem, already mentioned by other forecasters, is the trouble with verifying any fatalities. This will hinge on what the GJP considers credible evidence. Again, I can see a few or several people dying in a protest skirmish, but not ten. Will there be more than one clash?
Suspect so, but not sure if the info or data will be accurately reported outside Ru. Perhaps the question should/could account for this.

Putin is a strong man authoritarian who I would expect to crack down hard if faced with the prospect of significant anti-government protests that could reasonably challenge his rule. I would expect any extended or large anti-government protest to be cracked down on hard and reach the 10+ body count quickly. (I am a little worried about people "Disappearing" into cells forever rather than reported deaths for purposes of counting in this questions.)
Putin gives zero fucks who dies as long as he achieves his ends.

There have already been protests and conditions are likely to deteriorate further within the timeline of this question, so it seems reasonable to expect more protests to take place. The Russian government has made clear that they will act to prevent and stop any protests, so unfortunately it seems reasonable to also expect law enforcement to escalate in their abuse. Off the top of my (ignorant) head, I cannot think of any protests under Putin that have led to official deaths. The playbook seems to be mass arrests and what happens behind closed bars stays behind closed bars. There is an example that predates Putin, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Novocherkassk_massacre, but it took 30 years for it to be disclosed. For this reason, while I think that lethal violence may be deployed by Russian law enforcement if protests continue and intensify, I am not sure whether it will resolve the question because we may not have proof that satisfies the question by August 4th. However, there is a possibility that things will get to a point where some law enforcement agent decides to just drive into protestors, fire a gun, and so on... which if caught on camera might resolve the question.
